{"timestamp": "2025-12-06 20:26:51.456297", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting diagnosis report\n\nScope\n- Enterprise hierarchical network using OSPF. Key services: DHCP (central), DNS, Apache web servers (web0.local…web3.local), and an Nginx load balancer (web99.local) fronting backend web servers (which should not be directly reachable from hosts).\n- Focused on end-to-end health from user subnets 10.<core>.<dist>.0/24 to server farm 10.200.0.0/24.\n\nExecutive summary\n- Core routing and OSPF appear healthy; server farm services and DNS are reachable from at least one user LAN.\n- A critical anomaly exists in the 10.2.1.0/24 user subnet: host_2_1_1_1 has no IP address due to DHCP failure. Root cause localized to router_dist_2_1 where DHCP relay is not running. The DHCP server is up and reachable over L3, so the failure is specifically the relay function on the distribution router.\n- Backend web servers are not directly reachable from hosts, which matches the design.\n\nFindings and evidence\n\n1) End-to-end reachability baseline\n- get_reachability: Most sampled hosts can reach DNS (10.200.0.2) and other subnets with 0% loss and low RTTs (1–6 ms). Example: host_1_1_1_1 -> 10.200.0.2 ok; various 10.2.2.x hosts -> 10.200.0.2 ok.\n- Router_dist_2_1 OSPF routes present to user and server subnets:\n  - OSPF entries include 10.1.1.0/24, 10.1.2.0/24, 10.2.2.0/24, and 10.200.0.0/24 via 172.16.0.10 (functions.frr_show_ip_route).\n- L3 reachability between router_dist_2_1 and DHCP server is good:\n  - Ping router_dist_2_1 -> dhcp_server (10.200.0.8): 0% loss, ~2.2 ms (functions.ping_pair).\n\n2) Application layer checks (from a healthy host)\n- host_1_1_1_1:\n  - curl http://web99.local (Nginx LB): successful three times; name lookup and TTFB normal; total ~1.0–1.2 s (functions.curl_web_test).\n  - curl http://web0.local (Apache): successful with similar timings.\n  - Ping web_server_0 (10.200.0.3): 0% loss, RTT ~2–3 ms.\n- Attempt to reach a backend web server directly from host_1_1_1_1 fails with Destination Net Unreachable from 10.1.1.1 to 20.200.0.2 (functions.ping_pair). This aligns with the design that backends are not directly accessible.\n\n3) Anomaly in user subnet 10.2.1.0/24 (host_2_1_1_1)\n- get_reachability shows host_2_1_1_1 has no IP address assigned (null) and cannot be tested; status unknown.\n- host_2_1_1_1 interface state:\n  - eth0 up but no IPv4 address (functions.get_host_net_config). No routes present.\n- Access path L2/L3 state:\n  - switch_access_2_1_1 is bridging (br0) with member ports up; no obvious L2 faults (functions.get_host_net_config).\n  - router_dist_2_1 has br0 SVI 10.2.1.1/24 (default gateway) and OSPF is up; L3 routes are present (functions.get_host_net_config, functions.frr_show_ip_route).\n\n4) DHCP infrastructure\n- DHCP server:\n  - Listening on UDP/67; service is active (functions.netstat, functions.systemctl_ops).\n  - Reachable from router_dist_2_1 via ICMP.\n- DHCP relay on distribution routers:\n  - router_dist_2_1: isc-dhcp-relay is inactive (dead) (functions.systemctl_ops).\n  - router_dist_1_1: isc-dhcp-relay is also inactive (dead) (functions.systemctl_ops).\n  - Given that host_2_1_1_1 is in 10.2.1.0/24 and has no IP, the absence of a running DHCP relay on router_dist_2_1 explains why DHCP broadcasts from the access segment are not reaching the central DHCP server.\n\nAssessment\n\n- OSPF routing plane: Healthy. Routes propagate correctly across core and distribution. Latencies are low and consistent.\n- DNS and Web services: Functional from at least one user subnet. Load balancer access works; backend isolation enforced as designed (no direct reachability).\n- DHCP: Central server healthy and reachable. However, DHCP relay agents are not running on distribution routers. This is a functional outage for DHCP-dependent access segments.\n- Impacted segment: 10.2.1.0/24 (access path via switch_access_2_1_1 -> router_dist_2_1). Host host_2_1_1_1 cannot obtain an address, resulting in loss of IP connectivity.\n- Additional risk: router_dist_1_1 relay also inactive. Although host_1_1_1_1 currently has an address and connectivity, this may be due to an existing lease or non-DHCP configuration; new clients or lease expirations could be impacted in 10.1.1.0/24 as well.\n\nRoot cause\n- DHCP relay service (isc-dhcp-relay) is not running on router_dist_2_1, preventing DHCP Discover packets from the 10.2.1.0/24 broadcast domain from being relayed to the central DHCP server. This directly causes host_2_1_1_1 to have no IP configuration and no network connectivity.\n- A secondary misconfiguration exists on router_dist_1_1 where the relay is also inactive, posing a latent risk to the 10.1.1.0/24 segment.\n\nLocalization of faulty devices\n- Primary: router_dist_2_1 (distribution layer for 10.2.1.0/24) — DHCP relay service inactive.\n- Secondary observation: router_dist_1_1 — DHCP relay service inactive (potential future impact).\n\nNo remediation steps are provided as requested.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 12812, "output_tokens": 3498, "total_tokens": 16310, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 11776}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 2112}}}
